<exercises xml:id="practice-row-echelon-form">
    <introduction>
        <p>
            A few exercises related to the row reduced echelon form of a matrix are listed below.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <exercise>
        <p>
            Find the row reduced echelon form of the following matrices.
            <me>\begin{pmatrix}1\amp 2\amp -1\amp 2\\0\amp 0\amp 0\amp 0\\3\amp 1\amp -2\amp 0\end{pmatrix};\quad\begin{pmatrix}0\amp 1\amp -1\\0\amp -4\amp -1\\3\amp 3\amp 3\\-1\amp -1\amp -1\\2\amp 2\amp 2\end{pmatrix};\quad\begin{pmatrix}0\amp 1\\0\amp 0\end{pmatrix}
            </me>.
          </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <p>
            How many pivots are there in one row? How many pivots are there in one column?
          </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <p>
            In a <m>3\times 10</m> matrix what is the largest possible number of pivots?
          </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <p>
            Write the row reduced echelon matrix whose every row has a pivot.
          </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <p>
            Consider the following augmented matrices. In each case consider the corresponding system of linear equations and determine whether the system has no solution, a unique solution, or infinitely many solutions.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <me>
                    \left(
                      \begin{matrix}1\amp 0\amp 0\\0\amp 1\amp 0\\0\amp 0\amp 1\end{matrix}\left|\,\begin{matrix}4\\-1\\2\end{matrix}\right.
                    \right)
                  </me>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <me>\left(
                      \begin{matrix}1\amp 0\amp 1\\0\amp 1\amp 1\\0\amp 0\amp 0\end{matrix}\left|\,\begin{matrix}-2\\4\\0\end{matrix}\right.
                    \right)
                  </me>  
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <me>
                    \left(
                      \begin{matrix}1\amp 8\amp 1\\0\amp 1\amp 1\\0\amp 0\amp 0\end{matrix}\left|\,\begin{matrix}-2\\4\\1\end{matrix}\right.
                    \right)
                  </me>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <me>
                    \left(\begin{matrix}i\amp 0\amp 0\amp 0\\1\amp -i\amp 0\amp 0\\1\amp 2\amp i\amp 0\\1\amp 3\amp 3\amp -i\end{matrix}\left|\,\begin{matrix}1\\2\\3\\3\end{matrix}\right.\right),
                  </me>
                  where <m>i^2=-1</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider any square matrix of size <m>n</m> of your choice. Using row reduced echelon form determine whether your matrix is invertible or not (see <xref ref="def-inverse-of-matrix"/>).
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          List all possible types of elementary matrices of size <m>2</m> and <m>3</m>. Further show that these matrices are invertible.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A\in M_3(\K)</m>. Perform the row operation described in <xref ref="adding-scalar-multiple-of-row-to-other-row"/>, and denote the resulting matrix by <m>A^\prime</m>. Now perform the exact same operation on the identity matrix <m>I_3\in M_3(\K)</m>, and denote the resulting matrix by <m>E</m> (note that <m>E</m> is an elemetary matrix). Show that <m>EA=A^\prime</m>. What happens if we consider <m>AE</m> in terms of columns of <m>A</m>?
        </p>
        <p>
          Do the same exercise for other two row operations mentioned in <xref ref="def-elementary-row-operations"/>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the system of equations <m>AX=B</m> with <m>A\in M_{m\times n}(\R)</m> and <m>B\in M_{m\times 1}(\R)</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Show that if the above system has two distinct solutions then it has infinitely many solutions.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Show that this system has a solution in the complex numbers if and only if it has a solution in the real numbers.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A\in M_n(\K)</m>. Show that if the system <m>AX=B</m> has a unique solution for some particular <m>B\in M_{n\times 1}(\K)</m> then the system <m>AX=C</m> has a unique solution for any <m>C\in M_{n\times 1}(\K)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
</exercises>